{"title_page": "Paul Golding", "text_new": "{{infobox officeholder\n| name = Paul Golding\n| office = Leader of [[Britain First]]\n| image = File:Paul Golding.jpg\n| caption = Golding at a Britain First rally in 2014\n| deputy = None\n| successor = \n| party = [[Britain First]] (2011\u2013present)\n| otherparty = [[British National Party|BNP]] (unknown-2011)<br />[[National Front (UK)|National Front]] (previously)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1982|1|25}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Paul GOLDING|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/gyZjGZE5eve-4Uhjtj1fd6EXuXs/appointments|website=|publisher=Companies House|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref>\n|birth_place  = [[Camberwell]],{{cn|date=October 2019}} [[London]], England\n| term_start = 2014\n| term_end = \n}}\n[[file:Paul Golding (BF Leader) at Britain First rally.jpg|thumb|right|Golding at a Britain First rally in 2019]]\n'''Paul Anthony Golding'''{{cn|date=October 2019}} (born 25 January 1982){{cn|date=October 2019}} is a British [[Far-right politics|far-right]] political activist and the leader of [[Britain First]].\n\nIn December 2016, Golding was sentenced to eight weeks imprisonment for breaching a court order banning him from entering a mosque or encouraging others to do so in England and Wales. He took six months leave from the party and [[Jayda Fransen]], the deputy leader, acted as leader during his absence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.britainfirst.org/jayda-fransen-temporarily-assumes-leadership-of-britain-first/|title=Jayda Fransen temporarily assumes leadership of Britain First|last=Golding|first=Paul|date=November 2016|website=Britain First|publisher=Britain First|accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref> On 7 March 2018, Golding and Fransen were both imprisoned for religiously aggravated harassment.<ref>{{Cite news| work=[[The Guardian Online]] |title=Britain First leaders jailed over anti-Muslim hate crimes|date=7 March 2018| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/07/britain-first-leaders-convicted-of-anti-muslim-hate-crimes|accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===British National Party===\nGolding was a [[British National Party]] (BNP) [[Sevenoaks District]] councillor for St Mary's Ward in [[Swanley]] from 2009<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Chris|title=BNP wins seat on Sevenoaks district council|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/politics/article2027053.ece|work=The Times|url-access=subscription |date=21 February 2009}}</ref> to 2011.<ref name=\"UAF1\">{{cite web|title=FACTSHEET: Britain First: the fascist heirs of the BNP|url=http://uaf.org.uk/2015/04/factsheet-britain-first-the-fascist-heirs-of-the-bnp/|website=Unite Against Fascism|date=23 April 2015}}</ref> He was also a communications officer for the party.<ref name=\"UAF1\" />\n\nHe stood as BNP candidate for [[Sevenoaks (UK Parliament constituency)|Sevenoaks]] in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], and received 2.8% of the vote.<ref name=\"BBC10\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/d92.stm Sevenoaks], ''BBC News'' Election 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2008, it was reported that Golding had been expelled from the BNP for physically attacking Lawrence Rustem, a BNP [[Barking Borough Council]] councillor who is half-Turkish.<ref>{{cite news |title=BNP picks psychic and a gay porn director as candidates |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/bnp-picks-psychic-and-a-gay-porn-director-as-candidates-6676242.html |accessdate=7 September 2018 |work=Evening Standard |date=15 April 2008 |quote=Mr Rustem, a BNP councillor in Barking, is half-Turkish and was born Timucin Rustem.  His membership has been a sore point for BNP hardliners such as Paul Golding, the then editor of Identity, who was expelled from the party after physically attacking Mr Rustem.}}</ref>\n\n===Britain First===\nHe stood in the [[2014 United Kingdom local elections|2014 local elections]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tran|first1=Mark|title=Britain First leader complains of 'inquisition' after police grilling|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/may/14/britain-first-complaint-police-inquisition-london|accessdate=4 January 2017|work=The Guardian|date=14 May 2014}}</ref> and as a [[Britain First]] lead candidate in the [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2014 European Parliamentary election]] for [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]]; the party received 0.9% of the vote.<ref name=\"BBC14\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/eu-regions/W08000001 Vote 2014 - Wales], ''BBC News''</ref> Golding had been a member of the neo-Nazi [[National Front (UK)|National Front]] and once attended a Cenotaph on Remembrance Sunday wearing women's underwear on his head.<ref>[http://www.channel4.com/news/britain-first-far-right-anti-muslim-extremists-mosques \"Britain First: inside the extremist group targeting mosques\"], ''Channel 4 News'', 19 June 2014<br />- [http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/insider/the-shame-of-paul-golding-3616 \"The shame of Paul Golding\"], ''Hope not hate website'', 26 April 2014<br />- [http://politicalscrapbook.net/2014/11/paul-golding-cenotaph-knickers-britain-first/ \"Far-right leader turned up to Cenotaph with knickers on his head\"], ''Political Scrapbook'',10 November 2014</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Golding threatened to bury a pig at the site of proposed mosque in [[Dudley]], mistakenly believing this would contaminate the site and render it unsuitable.<ref>{{cite web|title = Britain First Leader Threatens To Bury Pig At Site Of Planned Mosque|author= Chris York| url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/05/10/britain-first-mega-mosque_n_7251368.html|website = The Huffington Post UK|date=10 May 2015|accessdate = 19 January 2016}}</ref> At the Britain First Annual Conference in November 2015, Golding and his deputy [[Jayda Fransen]] led the meeting which agreed a number of policies including banning the media from using the word 'racism' and abolishing the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Britain First: Public Can't Stop Laughing Over Far-Right Party's Plans To 'Ban Racism'|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/11/17/public-reaction-to-britain-first-plans-to-ban-racism_n_8583786.html|website = The Huffington Post UK|author=Steven Hopkins |date=17 November 2015| accessdate= 22 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe stood as a candidate in the [[2016 London mayoral election|London mayoral election in 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=York|first1=Chris|title=Britain First's Paul Golding To Stand In London Mayoral Election|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/09/27/britain-first-paul-golding-london-mayoral-election_n_8203000.html|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=22 January 2016|date=27 September 2015}}<br />- {{cite web|last1=Mogule|first1=Priyanka|title=Britain First leader Paul Golding to run for London mayor: Wants to hang opponents|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/britain-first-leader-paul-golding-run-london-mayor-wants-hang-opponents-1521415|work=International Business Times|accessdate=22 January 2016|date=27 September 2015}}</ref> He came eighth with 31,372 votes (1.2% of those cast) while [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]'s [[Sadiq Khan]] was elected as mayor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2016/london/results|title=London Elections, Candidates and Results|publisher=BBC News|date=May 2016|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Conservative Party ===\nIn December 2019, Golding announced that he was a paid-up member of the Bexleyheath and Crayford Conservative Association. He explained that he intended to \"help solidify Boris Johnson's control on the leadership, so we can achieve Brexit and hopefully cut immigration and confront radical Islam\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/paul-golding-conservatives-britain-first-boris-johnson-muslim-women-letterboxes-a9254061.html|title=Britain First leader officially joins Conservative Party: 'Boris Johnson is like us'|date=19 December 2019|website=The Independent|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> Shortly after the announcement, a Tory spokeswoman said that \"Paul Golding's application for membership of the Conservative Party has not been approved.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/britain-first-conservative-party-application-a4318191.html|title=Britain First leader's Conservative Party application 'not approved'|date=19 December 2019|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, Golding released a letter that he had received from the Conservative Party, informing him that his membership had been rejected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/britain-first-leader-paul-golding-21233754|title=Britain First leader Paul Golding rejected for Conservative Party membership|last=Milne|first=Oliver|date=7 January 2020|website=Daily Mirror|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nIn May 2014, Golding was arrested for criminal damage and breach of the peace during an [[Al-Muhajiroun]] protest outside the Indian Embassy in London.<ref>{{cite web|title = The Insider\u2019s blog: Outside the Indian Embassy now..|url = http://testsite.hopenothate.org.uk/outside-the-indian-embassy-now/|website = www.hopenothate.org.uk|author=Matthew Collins |date= 9 May 2014|accessdate = 22 January 2016}}</ref> In July 2014, he tried to have himself arrested at [[Bexleyheath]] police station over an incident at [[Crayford]] Mosque, but failed, an act widely considered to be a fund-raising publicity stunt.<ref>{{cite web|title = Far right leader Paul Golding tries to give himself up for arrest \u2013 and fails|author=Tim MacFarlan |date= 17 July 2014 |url = http://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/11348598.Far_right_leader_Paul_Golding_tries_to_give_himself_up_for_arrest_____and_fails/|website = News Shopper|accessdate = 22 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Agency]] accused Britain First of illegally using an image of the royal crown in its logo, ordering all images of the crown to be removed from Britain First's official website, marketing materials and merchandise \"with immediate effect\". Golding responded by calling the ASA a \"toothless quango with no power which no one takes any notice of\" and refused to change Britain First's logo.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Butler|first1=Sarah|title=BNP offshoot Britain First rapped by ASA for using royal symbols|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/27/bnp-britain-first-asa-advertising-breach-use-royal-symbols|work=The Guardian|date=26 August 2014}}<br />- {{cite news|last1=Butler|first1=Sarah|title=Government considers steps against Britain First over use of crown|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/27/government-cabinet-office-first-britain-royal-crown|work=The Guardian|date=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, he was arrested on suspicion of assault during a Britain First march in [[Derby]], as was an opponent who Golding had claimed assaulted him.<ref>{{cite web|title = I'll be back, says Britain First party leader Paul Golding after claiming he was attacked in Derby|url = http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/ll-says-Britain-party-leader-claiming-attacked/story-26138233-detail/story.html|website = Derby Telegraph| date=9 March 2015 |author= Zena Hawley|accessdate = 22 January 2016}}</ref> Also in 2015, Golding was convicted of harassing a woman, after mistakenly arriving at her home instead of that of a man allegedly linked to the [[7 July 2005 London bombings|2005 London bombings]]. He was also found guilty of wearing a political uniform, an offence under the [[Public Order Act 1936]]. A restraining order was issued against Golding and he was fined for both offences.<ref>Sam Balls, [http://www.essexchronicle.co.uk/Britain-leader-Paul-Golding-guilty/story-25808029-detail/story.html \"Britain First leader Paul Golding found guilty of harassment and wearing a political uniform\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511142820/http://www.essexchronicle.co.uk/Britain-leader-Paul-Golding-guilty/story-25808029-detail/story.html |date=2016-05-11 }}, ''Essex Chronicle'', 6 January 2015. Retrieved 22 January 2016.</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Golding and acting leader Jayda Fransen were arrested and charged with religious harassment. They were both bailed to appeared before [[Medway]] [[magistrate]]s in October 2017. Their arrests followed an investigation by [[Kent Police]] into the distribution of leaflets in the Thanet and Canterbury areas, and the posting of online videos during a trial at Canterbury Crown Court in May 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-41338328|title=Britain First leaders charged with religious harassment|last=|first=|date=20 September 2017|website=BBC News|access-date=20 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nGolding's Twitter account is withheld in Germany.<ref>Joseph Cox, [https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/this-is-how-twitter-blocks-far-right-tweets-in-germany \"This Is How Twitter Blocks Far-Right Tweets in Germany\"], ''Vice Motherboard'', 13 June 2017. Retrieved 13 June 2017.</ref>\n\n===December 2016 arrest and resignation===\nIn December 2016, Golding was sentenced to eight weeks in prison for breaching a court order banning him from entering a mosque or encouraging others to do so in England and Wales. Nine days after the imposition of the court injunction, Golding drove others to a mosque in Cardiff; they entered and mosque members found their behaviour provocative and unnerving. They feared the situation could have escalated if prayers had still been going on.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38326446 \"Ex-Britain First leader Paul Golding jailed over mosque ban\"], ''[[BBC News]]'', 15 December 2016</ref>\n\nLeadership of Britain First was passed on to the former deputy leader [[Jayda Fransen]] in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gable|first1=Gerry|title=More questions than answers: a Searchlight investigation|url=http://www.searchlightmagazine.com/2016/12/more-questions-than-answers-a-searchlight-investigation/|accessdate=7 December 2016|work=Searchlight|date=1 December 2016|language=en}}</ref> Fransen claimed that Golding was taking 6 months leave as leader of the organisation \"to address some important, personal family issues\".<ref>{{cite av media|last=Fransen|first=Jayda|title=Paul Golding in Muslim-run PRISON! A message from Jayda Fransen|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ybgK3f-D2TQ|date=21 December 2016|publisher=Britain First}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Satire|satirical]] news web site, ''[[The Rochdale Herald]]'', capitalised on the incident by inviting readers to [[sponsor (commercial)|sponsor]] his incarceration<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/paul-goldings-sponsored-jail-term_uk_585ebeebe4b0f24da6e79952|title=Paul Golding\u2019s Sponsored Jail Term Raises Over \u00a35,000 For Refugee Council|date=24 December 2016|work=HuffPost UK|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref> to raise money for refugees.\n\nOn 7 November 2017, Golding was sentenced to a 120-day suspended prison sentence and ordered to carry out 200 hours of unpaid community work by Sevenoaks Magistrates' Court after admitting a charge of assault by beating. He was also told to pay \u00a3750 compensation to his victim, plus \u00a3115 [[victim surcharge]] and \u00a385 prosecution costs. Summing up, magistrate Alan Austen described it as \"a really nasty and vicious assault in a public place\".<ref>Debbie King, [http://www.kentlive.news/news/britain-first-leader-paul-golding-739512 \"Britain First leader Paul Golding ordered to carry out community service for 'really nasty' night club attack\"], 7 November 2017</ref>\n\n===Alleged sex attack===\nIn late 2017, accusations were made against Golding by a female under the age of consent, who attended one of the group rallies protesting against the sexual abuse of young girls, that Golding had sexually abused her.<ref>John Simpson, [https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/britain-first-leader-paul-golding-in-sex-attack-case-xfc6w9066 \"Britain First leader Paul Golding in \u2018sex attack\u2019 case\"], ''The Times'', 1 December 2017, p 13</ref> Graham Morris, a former Britain First member, had claimed that the deputy leader, Jayda Fransen, had encouraged the victim to stay quiet, saying, \"I can give everything you need, a platform. I\u2019ll do this for you, that for you.\" <ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/dec/03/jayda-fransen-tried-to-stop-sex-assault-complaint \"Britain First\u2019s Jayda Fransen \u2018tried to halt sex assault complaint\u2019\"], ''The Observer'', 3 December 2017</ref>\n\n===2017 arrest===\nIn December 2017, on a reported visit to Belfast to support Jayda Fransen, Golding was arrested by the [[Police Service of Northern Ireland]] for a speech he gave in the city in August,<ref>{{cite news|last=Dearden |first=Lizzie |date=14 December 2017 |title=Britain First leader Paul Golding arrested while attending deputy's court hearing in Belfast |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/paul-golding-arrested-belfast-police-britain-first-leader-latest-jayda-fransen-court-hearing-a8110296.html |work=Independent |accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref> and was later charged.<ref>{{cite news|date=14 December 2017 |title=Britain First's Paul Golding and Jayda Fransen charged|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-42359462 |work=BBC News |accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018 conviction===\nOn 7 March 2018, Fransen and Golding were found guilty of religiously aggravated harassment at Folkestone Magistrates' Court, as a result of an investigation concerning the distribution of leaflets in 2017 in the Thanet and Canterbury areas. The pair were convicted over an incident at a takeaway in Ramsgate, Kent, during which Fransen screamed \u201cpaedophile\u201d and \u201cforeigner\u201d, while Fransen was also convicted for approaching a mistaken address she believed to belong to a Muslim defendant on a rape trial. They were both sentenced to prison, with 9 months for Fransen and 18 weeks for Golding.<ref>{{Cite news| work=[[The Guardian Online]] |title=Britain First leaders jailed over anti-Muslim hate crimes| date=7 March 2018| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/07/britain-first-leaders-convicted-of-anti-muslim-hate-crimes|accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 arrest===\nIn November 2018, Golding was charged with a number of offences related to anti-immigration leaflets distributed in [[Ballymena]], Co Antrim, and was charged with three counts of publishing written material intended to stir up hatred and one count of using threatening, abusive, insulting words or behaviour.<ref>Claire McNeilly, [https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/farright-rally-will-go-ahead-in-ballymena-despite-arrest-of-party-leader-37459454.html \"Far-right rally will go ahead in Ballymena despite arrest of party leader\"], ''Belfast Telegraph'', 26 October 2018. Retrieved 10 November 2018.<br />- [https://www.irishnews.com/news/northernirelandnews/2018/10/26/news/britain-first-leader-paul-golding-charged-over-anti-immigration-leaflets-in-co-antrim-1469830/ \"Britain First leader Paul Golding charged over anti-immigration leaflets in Co Antrim\"], ''The Irish News'', 26 October 2018. Retrieved 10 November 2018.</ref> In June 2019, he was sentenced to three months imprisonment, suspended for two years.<ref>[https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/probation-for-northern-ireland-man-who-handed-out-hate-leaflets-with-britain-first-leader-38347279.html \"Probation for Northern Ireland man who handed out hate leaflets with Britain First leader\"], ''Belfast Telegraph'', 26 July 2019. Retrieved 31 August 2019.</ref>\n\n===2020 terrorism charge===\nIn February Golding was charged under the Terrorism Act for refusing to provide police at Heathrow Airport with the PIN code for his phone. Golding was stopped at Heathrow airport in October 2019, while returning from a trip to the Russian parliament, by officers from the Metropolitan police's counter-terrorism command.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Nadeem|last1=Badshah|accessdate=2020-02-21|title=Britain First leader Paul Golding charged by anti-terror police|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/feb/21/britain-first-leader-paul-golding-charged-by-anti-terror-police|newspaper=The Guardian|date=21 February 2020|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==Donald Trump retweets==\n{{main|Donald Trump on social media#Britain First videos}}\nOn 29 November 2017, US president [[Donald Trump]] [[retweet]]ed three anti-Muslim videos shared by Jayda Fransen on her [[Twitter|Twitter account]] supporting her views.<ref>{{Cite news| newspaper=BBC News |title=Trump Twitter account retweets incendiary videos| date=29 November 2017| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-42166663}}</ref> Three weeks later, on 18 December, Twitter suspended the accounts of Golding, Fransen and Britain First for inciting racial hatred.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2017/12/18/twitter-purge-suspends-account-of-far-right-leader-who-was-retweeted-by-trump/ |title=\u2018Twitter purge\u2019 suspends account of far-right leader who was retweeted by Trump |first=Craig |last=Timberg |first2=Hayley |last2=Tsukayama |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |date=18 December 2017}}</ref> They later joined and asked their followers to go to the [[Gab (social network)|Gab]] social networking service created as an alternative to social networks like Facebook, Twitter and Reddit.<ref>Sarah Marsh, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/20/britain-first-gab-social-media-twitter-ban \"Britain First signs up to fringe social media site after Twitter ban\"], ''The Guardian'', 20 December 2017.</ref>\n\n==Elections contested==\n'''UK general elections'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date of election !! Constituency !! Party !! Votes !! % !! Result \n|-\n| [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]] || [[Sevenoaks (UK Parliament constituency)|Sevenoaks]] || [[British National Party|BNP]] || 1,384 || 2.8<ref name=\"BBC10\"/> || Not elected\n|}\n\n'''European Parliament elections'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Region !! Party !! Votes !! % !! Result !! Notes\n|-\n| [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2014]] || [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]] || [[Britain First]] || 6,633 || 0.9 || Not elected<ref name=\"BBC14\"/> || Multi member constituencies; party list\n|}\n\n'''London mayoral election'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Party !! Votes !! % !! Result\n|-\n| [[2016 London mayoral election|2016]] || [[Britain First]] || 31,372 || 1.2 || Not elected\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golding, Paul}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Anti-Muslim sentiment]]\n[[Category:British National Party people]]\n[[Category:British Eurosceptics]]\n[[Category:British politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:British critics of Islam]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Kent]]\n[[Category:English far-right politicians]]\n[[Category:Islamophobia in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Opposition to Islam in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People convicted of harassment]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of England and Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox officeholder\n| name = Paul Golding\n| office = Leader of [[Britain First]]\n| image = File:Paul Golding.jpg\n| caption = Golding at a Britain First rally in 2014\n| deputy = None\n| successor = \n| party = [[Britain First]] (2011\u2013present)\n| otherparty = [[British National Party|BNP]] (unknown-2011)<br />[[National Front (UK)|National Front]] (previously)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1982|1|25}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Paul GOLDING|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/gyZjGZE5eve-4Uhjtj1fd6EXuXs/appointments|website=|publisher=Companies House|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref>\n|birth_place  = [[Camberwell]],{{cn|date=October 2019}} [[London]], England\n| term_start = 2014\n| term_end = \n}}\n[[file:Paul Golding (BF Leader) at Britain First rally.jpg|thumb|right|Golding at a Britain First rally in 2019]]\n'''Paul Anthony Golding'''{{cn|date=October 2019}} (born 25 January 1982){{cn|date=October 2019}} is a British [[Far-right politics|far-right]] political activist and the leader of [[Britain First]].\n\nIn December 2016, Golding was sentenced to eight weeks imprisonment for breaching a court order banning him from entering a mosque or encouraging others to do so in England and Wales. He took six months leave from the party and [[Jayda Fransen]], the deputy leader, acted as leader during his absence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.britainfirst.org/jayda-fransen-temporarily-assumes-leadership-of-britain-first/|title=Jayda Fransen temporarily assumes leadership of Britain First|last=Golding|first=Paul|date=November 2016|website=Britain First|publisher=Britain First|accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref> On 7 March 2018, Golding and Fransen were both imprisoned for religiously aggravated harassment.<ref>{{Cite news| work=[[The Guardian Online]] |title=Britain First leaders jailed over anti-Muslim hate crimes|date=7 March 2018| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/07/britain-first-leaders-convicted-of-anti-muslim-hate-crimes|accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===British National Party===\nGolding was a [[British National Party]] (BNP) [[Sevenoaks District]] councillor for St Mary's Ward in [[Swanley]] from 2009<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Chris|title=BNP wins seat on Sevenoaks district council|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/politics/article2027053.ece|work=The Times|url-access=subscription |date=21 February 2009}}</ref> to 2011.<ref name=\"UAF1\">{{cite web|title=FACTSHEET: Britain First: the fascist heirs of the BNP|url=http://uaf.org.uk/2015/04/factsheet-britain-first-the-fascist-heirs-of-the-bnp/|website=Unite Against Fascism|date=23 April 2015}}</ref> He was also a communications officer for the party.<ref name=\"UAF1\" />\n\nHe stood as BNP candidate for [[Sevenoaks (UK Parliament constituency)|Sevenoaks]] in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], and received 2.8% of the vote.<ref name=\"BBC10\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/d92.stm Sevenoaks], ''BBC News'' Election 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2008, it was reported that Golding had been expelled from the BNP for physically attacking Lawrence Rustem, a BNP [[Barking Borough Council]] councillor who is half-Turkish.<ref>{{cite news |title=BNP picks psychic and a gay porn director as candidates |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/bnp-picks-psychic-and-a-gay-porn-director-as-candidates-6676242.html |accessdate=7 September 2018 |work=Evening Standard |date=15 April 2008 |quote=Mr Rustem, a BNP councillor in Barking, is half-Turkish and was born Timucin Rustem.  His membership has been a sore point for BNP hardliners such as Paul Golding, the then editor of Identity, who was expelled from the party after physically attacking Mr Rustem.}}</ref>\n\n===Britain First===\nHe stood in the [[2014 United Kingdom local elections|2014 local elections]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tran|first1=Mark|title=Britain First leader complains of 'inquisition' after police grilling|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/may/14/britain-first-complaint-police-inquisition-london|accessdate=4 January 2017|work=The Guardian|date=14 May 2014}}</ref> and as a [[Britain First]] lead candidate in the [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2014 European Parliamentary election]] for [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]]; the party received 0.9% of the vote.<ref name=\"BBC14\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/eu-regions/W08000001 Vote 2014 - Wales], ''BBC News''</ref> Golding had been a member of the neo-Nazi [[National Front (UK)|National Front]] and once attended a Cenotaph on Remembrance Sunday wearing women's underwear on his head.<ref>[http://www.channel4.com/news/britain-first-far-right-anti-muslim-extremists-mosques \"Britain First: inside the extremist group targeting mosques\"], ''Channel 4 News'', 19 June 2014<br />- [http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/insider/the-shame-of-paul-golding-3616 \"The shame of Paul Golding\"], ''Hope not hate website'', 26 April 2014<br />- [http://politicalscrapbook.net/2014/11/paul-golding-cenotaph-knickers-britain-first/ \"Far-right leader turned up to Cenotaph with knickers on his head\"], ''Political Scrapbook'',10 November 2014</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Golding threatened to bury a pig at the site of proposed mosque in [[Dudley]], mistakenly believing this would contaminate the site and render it unsuitable.<ref>{{cite web|title = Britain First Leader Threatens To Bury Pig At Site Of Planned Mosque|author= Chris York| url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/05/10/britain-first-mega-mosque_n_7251368.html|website = The Huffington Post UK|date=10 May 2015|accessdate = 19 January 2016}}</ref> At the Britain First Annual Conference in November 2015, Golding and his deputy [[Jayda Fransen]] led the meeting which agreed a number of policies including banning the media from using the word 'racism' and abolishing the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Britain First: Public Can't Stop Laughing Over Far-Right Party's Plans To 'Ban Racism'|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/11/17/public-reaction-to-britain-first-plans-to-ban-racism_n_8583786.html|website = The Huffington Post UK|author=Steven Hopkins |date=17 November 2015| accessdate= 22 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe stood as a candidate in the [[2016 London mayoral election|London mayoral election in 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=York|first1=Chris|title=Britain First's Paul Golding To Stand In London Mayoral Election|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/09/27/britain-first-paul-golding-london-mayoral-election_n_8203000.html|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=22 January 2016|date=27 September 2015}}<br />- {{cite web|last1=Mogule|first1=Priyanka|title=Britain First leader Paul Golding to run for London mayor: Wants to hang opponents|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/britain-first-leader-paul-golding-run-london-mayor-wants-hang-opponents-1521415|work=International Business Times|accessdate=22 January 2016|date=27 September 2015}}</ref> He came eighth with 31,372 votes (1.2% of those cast) while [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]'s [[Sadiq Khan]] was elected as mayor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2016/london/results|title=London Elections, Candidates and Results|publisher=BBC News|date=May 2016|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Conservative Party ===\nIn December 2019, Golding announced that he was a paid-up member of the Bexleyheath and Crayford Conservative Association. He explained that he intended to \"help solidify Boris Johnson's control on the leadership, so we can achieve Brexit and hopefully cut immigration and confront radical Islam\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/paul-golding-conservatives-britain-first-boris-johnson-muslim-women-letterboxes-a9254061.html|title=Britain First leader officially joins Conservative Party: 'Boris Johnson is like us'|date=19 December 2019|website=The Independent|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> Shortly after the announcement, a Tory spokeswoman said that \"Paul Golding's application for membership of the Conservative Party has not been approved.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/britain-first-conservative-party-application-a4318191.html|title=Britain First leader's Conservative Party application 'not approved'|date=19 December 2019|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, Golding released a letter that he had received from the Conservative Party, informing him that his membership had been rejected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/britain-first-leader-paul-golding-21233754|title=Britain First leader Paul Golding rejected for Conservative Party membership|last=Milne|first=Oliver|date=7 January 2020|website=Daily Mirror|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nIn May 2014, Golding was arrested for criminal damage and breach of the peace during an [[Al-Muhajiroun]] protest outside the Indian Embassy in London.<ref>{{cite web|title = The Insider\u2019s blog: Outside the Indian Embassy now..|url = http://testsite.hopenothate.org.uk/outside-the-indian-embassy-now/|website = www.hopenothate.org.uk|author=Matthew Collins |date= 9 May 2014|accessdate = 22 January 2016}}</ref> In July 2014, he tried to have himself arrested at [[Bexleyheath]] police station over an incident at [[Crayford]] Mosque, but failed, an act widely considered to be a fund-raising publicity stunt.<ref>{{cite web|title = Far right leader Paul Golding tries to give himself up for arrest \u2013 and fails|author=Tim MacFarlan |date= 17 July 2014 |url = http://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/11348598.Far_right_leader_Paul_Golding_tries_to_give_himself_up_for_arrest_____and_fails/|website = News Shopper|accessdate = 22 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Agency]] accused Britain First of illegally using an image of the royal crown in its logo, ordering all images of the crown to be removed from Britain First's official website, marketing materials and merchandise \"with immediate effect\". Golding responded by calling the ASA a \"toothless quango with no power which no one takes any notice of\" and refused to change Britain First's logo.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Butler|first1=Sarah|title=BNP offshoot Britain First rapped by ASA for using royal symbols|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/27/bnp-britain-first-asa-advertising-breach-use-royal-symbols|work=The Guardian|date=26 August 2014}}<br />- {{cite news|last1=Butler|first1=Sarah|title=Government considers steps against Britain First over use of crown|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/27/government-cabinet-office-first-britain-royal-crown|work=The Guardian|date=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, he was arrested on suspicion of assault during a Britain First march in [[Derby]], as was an opponent who Golding had claimed assaulted him.<ref>{{cite web|title = I'll be back, says Britain First party leader Paul Golding after claiming he was attacked in Derby|url = http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/ll-says-Britain-party-leader-claiming-attacked/story-26138233-detail/story.html|website = Derby Telegraph| date=9 March 2015 |author= Zena Hawley|accessdate = 22 January 2016}}</ref> Also in 2015, Golding was convicted of harassing a woman, after mistakenly arriving at her home instead of that of a man allegedly linked to the [[7 July 2005 London bombings|2005 London bombings]]. He was also found guilty of wearing a political uniform, an offence under the [[Public Order Act 1936]]. A restraining order was issued against Golding and he was fined for both offences.<ref>Sam Balls, [http://www.essexchronicle.co.uk/Britain-leader-Paul-Golding-guilty/story-25808029-detail/story.html \"Britain First leader Paul Golding found guilty of harassment and wearing a political uniform\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511142820/http://www.essexchronicle.co.uk/Britain-leader-Paul-Golding-guilty/story-25808029-detail/story.html |date=2016-05-11 }}, ''Essex Chronicle'', 6 January 2015. Retrieved 22 January 2016.</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Golding and acting leader Jayda Fransen were arrested and charged with religious harassment. They were both bailed to appeared before [[Medway]] [[magistrate]]s in October 2017. Their arrests followed an investigation by [[Kent Police]] into the distribution of leaflets in the Thanet and Canterbury areas, and the posting of online videos during a trial at Canterbury Crown Court in May 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-41338328|title=Britain First leaders charged with religious harassment|last=|first=|date=20 September 2017|website=BBC News|access-date=20 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nGolding's Twitter account is withheld in Germany.<ref>Joseph Cox, [https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/this-is-how-twitter-blocks-far-right-tweets-in-germany \"This Is How Twitter Blocks Far-Right Tweets in Germany\"], ''Vice Motherboard'', 13 June 2017. Retrieved 13 June 2017.</ref>\n\n===December 2016 arrest and resignation===\nIn December 2016, Golding was sentenced to eight weeks in prison for breaching a court order banning him from entering a mosque or encouraging others to do so in England and Wales. Nine days after the imposition of the court injunction, Golding drove others to a mosque in Cardiff; they entered and mosque members found their behaviour provocative and unnerving. They feared the situation could have escalated if prayers had still been going on.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38326446 \"Ex-Britain First leader Paul Golding jailed over mosque ban\"], ''[[BBC News]]'', 15 December 2016</ref>\n\nLeadership of Britain First was passed on to the former deputy leader [[Jayda Fransen]] in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gable|first1=Gerry|title=More questions than answers: a Searchlight investigation|url=http://www.searchlightmagazine.com/2016/12/more-questions-than-answers-a-searchlight-investigation/|accessdate=7 December 2016|work=Searchlight|date=1 December 2016|language=en}}</ref> Fransen claimed that Golding was taking 6 months leave as leader of the organisation \"to address some important, personal family issues\".<ref>{{cite av media|last=Fransen|first=Jayda|title=Paul Golding in Muslim-run PRISON! A message from Jayda Fransen|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ybgK3f-D2TQ|date=21 December 2016|publisher=Britain First}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Satire|satirical]] news web site, ''[[The Rochdale Herald]]'', capitalised on the incident by inviting readers to [[sponsor (commercial)|sponsor]] his incarceration<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/paul-goldings-sponsored-jail-term_uk_585ebeebe4b0f24da6e79952|title=Paul Golding\u2019s Sponsored Jail Term Raises Over \u00a35,000 For Refugee Council|date=24 December 2016|work=HuffPost UK|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref> to raise money for refugees.\n\nOn 7 November 2017, Golding was sentenced to a 120-day suspended prison sentence and ordered to carry out 200 hours of unpaid community work by Sevenoaks Magistrates' Court after admitting a charge of assault by beating. He was also told to pay \u00a3750 compensation to his victim, plus \u00a3115 [[victim surcharge]] and \u00a385 prosecution costs. Summing up, magistrate Alan Austen described it as \"a really nasty and vicious assault in a public place\".<ref>Debbie King, [http://www.kentlive.news/news/britain-first-leader-paul-golding-739512 \"Britain First leader Paul Golding ordered to carry out community service for 'really nasty' night club attack\"], 7 November 2017</ref>\n\n===Alleged sex attack===\nIn late 2017, accusations were made against Golding by a female under the age of consent, who attended one of the group rallies protesting against the sexual abuse of young girls, that Golding had sexually abused her.<ref>John Simpson, [https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/britain-first-leader-paul-golding-in-sex-attack-case-xfc6w9066 \"Britain First leader Paul Golding in \u2018sex attack\u2019 case\"], ''The Times'', 1 December 2017, p 13</ref> Graham Morris, a former Britain First member, had claimed that the deputy leader, Jayda Fransen, had encouraged the victim to stay quiet, saying, \"I can give everything you need, a platform. I\u2019ll do this for you, that for you.\" <ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/dec/03/jayda-fransen-tried-to-stop-sex-assault-complaint \"Britain First\u2019s Jayda Fransen \u2018tried to halt sex assault complaint\u2019\"], ''The Observer'', 3 December 2017</ref>\n\n===2017 arrest===\nIn December 2017, on a reported visit to Belfast to support Jayda Fransen, Golding was arrested by the [[Police Service of Northern Ireland]] for a speech he gave in the city in August,<ref>{{cite news|last=Dearden |first=Lizzie |date=14 December 2017 |title=Britain First leader Paul Golding arrested while attending deputy's court hearing in Belfast |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/paul-golding-arrested-belfast-police-britain-first-leader-latest-jayda-fransen-court-hearing-a8110296.html |work=Independent |accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref> and was later charged.<ref>{{cite news|date=14 December 2017 |title=Britain First's Paul Golding and Jayda Fransen charged|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-42359462 |work=BBC News |accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018 conviction===\nOn 7 March 2018, Fransen and Golding were found guilty of religiously aggravated harassment at Folkestone Magistrates' Court, as a result of an investigation concerning the distribution of leaflets in 2017 in the Thanet and Canterbury areas. The pair were convicted over an incident at a takeaway in Ramsgate, Kent, during which Fransen screamed \u201cpaedophile\u201d and \u201cforeigner\u201d, while Fransen was also convicted for approaching a mistaken address she believed to belong to a Muslim defendant on a rape trial. They were both sentenced to prison, with 9 months for Fransen and 18 weeks for Golding.<ref>{{Cite news| work=[[The Guardian Online]] |title=Britain First leaders jailed over anti-Muslim hate crimes| date=7 March 2018| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/07/britain-first-leaders-convicted-of-anti-muslim-hate-crimes|accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 arrest===\nIn November 2018, Golding was charged with a number of offences related to anti-immigration leaflets distributed in [[Ballymena]], Co Antrim, and was charged with three counts of publishing written material intended to stir up hatred and one count of using threatening, abusive, insulting words or behaviour.<ref>Claire McNeilly, [https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/farright-rally-will-go-ahead-in-ballymena-despite-arrest-of-party-leader-37459454.html \"Far-right rally will go ahead in Ballymena despite arrest of party leader\"], ''Belfast Telegraph'', 26 October 2018. Retrieved 10 November 2018.<br />- [https://www.irishnews.com/news/northernirelandnews/2018/10/26/news/britain-first-leader-paul-golding-charged-over-anti-immigration-leaflets-in-co-antrim-1469830/ \"Britain First leader Paul Golding charged over anti-immigration leaflets in Co Antrim\"], ''The Irish News'', 26 October 2018. Retrieved 10 November 2018.</ref> In June 2019, he was sentenced to three months imprisonment, suspended for two years.<ref>[https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/probation-for-northern-ireland-man-who-handed-out-hate-leaflets-with-britain-first-leader-38347279.html \"Probation for Northern Ireland man who handed out hate leaflets with Britain First leader\"], ''Belfast Telegraph'', 26 July 2019. Retrieved 31 August 2019.</ref>\n\n===2020 terrorism charge===\nIn February Golding was charged under the Terrorism Act for refusing to provide police at Heathrow Airport with the PIN code for his phone. Golding was stopped at Heathrow airport in October 2019, while returning from a trip to the Russian parliament, by officers from the Metropolitan police\u2019s counter-terrorism command.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Nadeem|last1=Badshah|accessdate=2020-02-21|title=Britain First leader Paul Golding charged by anti-terror police|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/feb/21/britain-first-leader-paul-golding-charged-by-anti-terror-police|newspaper=The Guardian|date=21 February 2020|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==Donald Trump retweets==\n{{main|Donald Trump on social media#Britain First videos}}\nOn 29 November 2017, US president [[Donald Trump]] [[retweet]]ed three anti-Muslim videos shared by Jayda Fransen on her [[Twitter|Twitter account]] supporting her views.<ref>{{Cite news| newspaper=BBC News |title=Trump Twitter account retweets incendiary videos| date=29 November 2017| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-42166663}}</ref> Three weeks later, on 18 December, Twitter suspended the accounts of Golding, Fransen and Britain First for inciting racial hatred.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2017/12/18/twitter-purge-suspends-account-of-far-right-leader-who-was-retweeted-by-trump/ |title=\u2018Twitter purge\u2019 suspends account of far-right leader who was retweeted by Trump |first=Craig |last=Timberg |first2=Hayley |last2=Tsukayama |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |date=18 December 2017}}</ref> They later joined and asked their followers to go to the [[Gab (social network)|Gab]] social networking service created as an alternative to social networks like Facebook, Twitter and Reddit.<ref>Sarah Marsh, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/20/britain-first-gab-social-media-twitter-ban \"Britain First signs up to fringe social media site after Twitter ban\"], ''The Guardian'', 20 December 2017.</ref>\n\n==Elections contested==\n'''UK general elections'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date of election !! Constituency !! Party !! Votes !! % !! Result \n|-\n| [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]] || [[Sevenoaks (UK Parliament constituency)|Sevenoaks]] || [[British National Party|BNP]] || 1,384 || 2.8<ref name=\"BBC10\"/> || Not elected\n|}\n\n'''European Parliament elections'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Region !! Party !! Votes !! % !! Result !! Notes\n|-\n| [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2014]] || [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]] 