ren's Book Award\n| Notable\n| 2004\n| {{sort|Smith,Patricia|[[Patricia Smith (poet)|Patricia Smith]]}}\n| ''Janna and the Kings''\n|-\n| [[Belpre Medal|Pura Belpr\u00e9 Illustrator Award]]\n| Honor\n| 2010\n| {{sort|Parra,John|John Parra}}\n| ''Gracias \u2022 Thanks''\n|-\n| [[Belpre Medal|Pura Belpr\u00e9 Illustrator Award]]\n| Honor\n| 2006\n| {{sort|Delacre,Lulu|[[Lulu Delacre]]}}\n| ''Arrorr\u00f3, mi ni\u00f1o: Latino Lullabies and Gentle Games''\n|-\n| [[Belpre Medal|Pura Belpr\u00e9 Illustrator Award]]\n| Honor\n| 2004\n| {{sort|Casilla,Robert|Robert Casilla}}\n| ''First Day in Grapes''\n|-\n| [[Belpre Medal|Pura Belpr\u00e9 Illustrator Award]]\n| Honor\n| 2004\n| {{sort|Diaz,David|[[David D\u00edaz (illustrator)|David Diaz]]}}\n| ''The Pot that Juan Built''\n|}\n\n==Notable authors and illustrators==\nAuthors and illustrators with work published by Lee & Low Books include:\n\n*[[Lulu Delacre]]\n*[[Ted Lewin]]\n*[[Betsy Lewin]]\n*[[Joseph Bruchac]]\n*[[Ed Young (illustrator)|Ed Young]]\n*[[Rosa Parks]]\n*[[Carole Boston Weatherford]]\n*[[Pat Mora]]\n*[[David D\u00edaz (illustrator)|David Diaz]]\n*[[George Ancona]]\n*[[John Coy]]\n*[[Lynne Barasch]]\n*[[Benny Andrews]]\n*[[James Haskins|Jim Haskins]]\n*[[Chris Soentpiet]]\n*[[Greg Neri]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n*[[Media of New York City]]\n*[[List of publishers of children's books]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.leeandlow.com/ Lee & Low official website]\n* [http://ccbc.education.wisc.edu/books/pcstats.asp/ Publishing Statistics on Children's Books about People of Color and First/Native Nations and by People of Color and First/Native Nations Authors and Illustrators Documented by the Cooperative Children's Book Center School of Education, University of Wisconsin-Madison]\n* [https://americanindiansinchildrensliterature.blogspot.com/ American Indians in Children's Literature (AICL)]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee and Low Books}}\n[[Category:Children's book publishers]]\n[[Category:Book publishing companies based in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1991]]\n[[Category:1991 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox publisher\n| image        = [[Image:Leeandlowbookslogo.jpg]]\n| parent       = \n| status       = \n| founded      = 1991\n| founder      = Philip Lee and Tom Low \n| successor    = \n| country      = [[Image:Flag of the United States.svg|20px]] United States|\n| headquarters = [[New York City]]\n| distribution = self-distributed (US)<br>[[Fitzhenry & Whiteside]] (Canada)<ref>[https://www.fitzhenry.ca/other-publishers Publishers We Distribute]</ref>\n| keypeople    = '''Tom Low''' ([[President (corporate title)|President]])<br /> '''Jason Low''' (Vice President, [[Publisher]])<br /> '''Craig Low''' (Vice President, Publisher of Bebop Books)\n| publications = [[Book]]s, Games\n| topics       = \n| genre        = \n| imprints     = Tu Books<br>Bebop Books<br>Children's Book Press<br>Shen's Books<br>Lee & Low Games<br>Dive Into Reading\n| revenue      = \n| numemployees = \n| nasdaq       = \n| url          = {{URL|http://www.leeandlow.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Lee & Low Books''' is an independent children's book publisher focusing on diversity.\n\n==History==\n'''Lee & Low''' was founded in 1991 by Chinese Americans Tom Low and Philip Lee as a children's book publisher specializing in books featuring people of color and one of the few minority-owned publishing companies in the United States.<ref name=\"Multicultural Review,\">\"Descubriendo el sabor: Spanish Bilingual Book Publishing and Cultural Authenticity,\" [http://www.mcreview.com/index.html ''Multicultural Review,''] Winter 2007</ref> Low says, \"There was a void in children's books. Most of the books were targeted to Caucasians or contained animals or [[fairy tales]]. There was nothing dealing with contemporary issues and people of color.\".<ref>\"Trailblazers: A Storybook Tale,\" [http://www.audreymagazine.com/ ''Audrey / The Asian American Women's Lifestyle Magazine,''] June/July 2007.</ref> Lee & Low published its first list in 1993 and immediately gained attention when its first book, ''[[Baseball Saved Us]]'' was given a full-page review in ''[[The New York Times Book Review]].''<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/04/books/children-s-books-023693.html Children's Books: ''Baseball Saved Us, The New York Times Book Review''] Accessed April 2, 2009</ref>\n\nIn 1997, founder Tom Low's sons, Jason Low and Craig Low, joined Lee & Low, and in 2004, founder Philip Lee retired.<ref>[http://www.leeandlow.com/p/about_us.mhtml About Us] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415123728/http://www.leeandlow.com/p/about_us.mhtml |date=2009-04-15 }} Accessed April 1, 2009</ref>\n\nLee & Low Books publishes primarily [[picture books]], but in recent years has also published a small number of middle grade and [[young adult fiction|young adult]] titles.\n\nIn January 2012, Lee & Low Books acquired the backlist titles of the now-defunct non-profit publisher, Children's Book Press, as well as the latter's existing contracts with authors and illustrators, with the name itself being revived as an imprint of Lee & Low Books.<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-industry-news/article/50362-lee--low-acquires-children-s-book-press.html] Accessed March 2, 2012</ref>\n\n==Research==\nIn 2015, Lee & Low Books partnered with [[St.Catherine University]] and Assistant Professor Sarah Park Dahlen<ref>[https://www.stkate.edu/academics/our-faculty/sarah-park-dahlen/ Assistant Professor Sarah Park Dahlen] Accessed December 1, 2016</ref> to conduct the Diversity Baseline Survey (DBS). The objectives were to look at 1) Gender 2) Race/ethnicity 3) Sexual Orientation 4) Disability in the publishing industry.<ref>[https://www.leeandlow.com/about-us/the-diversity-baseline-survey Lee & Low Books, About the Diversity Baseline Survey] Accessed December 1, 2016</ref>\n\nThe Diversity Baseline Survey (DBS) was sent to 1,524 reviewer employees and 11,713 publishing employees for a total of 13,237 surveys deployed. The DBS survey results confirmed that the publishing industry is overwhelmingly white, at 79%,<ref>[http://blog.leeandlow.com/2016/01/26/where-is-the-diversity-in-publishing-the-2015-diversity-baseline-survey-results/ Lee & Low Books, ''Where is the Diversity in Publishing? The 2015 Diversity Baseline Results'']< Accessed December 1, 2016</ref> which corresponded with the numbers from ''[[Publishers Weekly]]''{{'s}} annual salary survey.<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/publisher-news/article/68405-publishing-industry-salary-survey-2015-a-younger-workforce-still-predominantly-white.html ''Publishers Weekly'' The PW Publishing Industry Salary Survey 2015: A Younger Workforce, Still Predominantly White] Accessed December 1, 2016</ref>\n\n==Arcoiris: books in Spanish==\nIn 1994, Lee & Low began to publish Spanish/English bilingual books and Spanish translations of many of their English titles.<ref name=\"Multicultural Review,\"/> The name '''Arcoiris''', Spanish for [[rainbow]], was chosen to reflect the diversity of the books and subject matter.<ref>[http://www.leeandlow.com/p/overview_arcoiris.mhtml Arcoiris: Books in Spanish] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225183919/http://www.leeandlow.com/p/overview_arcoiris.mhtml |date=2009-02-25 }}, accessed March 19, 2009</ref>\n\n==Bebop Books==\nFounded in 2000, '''Bebop Books''' is an educational imprint of Lee & Low. Bebop Books prints leveled books for early readers in English and Spanish.<ref>[http://www.leeandlow.com/p/overview_bebop.mhtml Bebop Books], accessed March 19, 2009</ref>\n\n==Tu Books==\n{{main|Tu Books}}\n'''Tu Books''' is an imprint of Lee & Low. Tu Books publishes middle grade and young adult science fiction, fantasy, and mystery featuring people of color or set in worlds inspired by non-Western folklore or culture.<ref>[http://www.leeandlow.com/p/tu_submissions.mhtml Tu Books Submission Guidelines], accessed October 27, 2010</ref>\n\nTu Books was founded as Tu Publishing in 2009 by [[Stacy Whitman]], a freelance children's book editor. In March 2010, Whitman joined Lee & Low as editorial director of the new imprint.<ref>[http://www.prweb.com/releases/2010/03/prweb3699034.htm Press Release: Lee & Low Books Acquires Tu Publishing, Brings Diversity to Fantasy and Science Fiction], accessed March 15, 2010</ref>\n\n==New Voices Award==\nIn 2000, Lee & Low Books established the New Voices Award to encourage writers of color. The award is open to any United States resident of color who has not had a children's [[picture book]] published previously. A winner receives $1000 and a standard publication contract, while an Honor Award winner receives $500. While Honor Award winners are not guaranteed publication, several honor books have been published.<ref>[http://www.leeandlow.com/p/new_voices_award.mhtml New Voices Award], accessed April 1, 2009</ref>\n\n'''New Voices Award recipients'''\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Author\n!Book\n!Citation\n!Published\n|- \n| 2009\n| {{sort|Solorzano,Tiare Williams|Tiare Williams Solorzano}}\n| ''Little Fish''\n| Honor\n| \n|- \n| 2008\n| {{sort|Charara,Hayan|Hayan Charara}}\n| {{sort|Three Lucys,The|''The Three Lucys''}}\n| Honor\n| \n|- style=\"background:LemonChiffon; color:black\"\n| 2007\n| {{sort|Tuck,Pamela M.|Pamela M. Tuck}}\n| {{sort|Fly in a Bowl of Milk,A|''A Fly in a Bowl of Milk''}}\n| Winner\n| ''2012''\n|- \n| 2007\n| {{sort|Yamasaki,Katie|Katie Yamasaki}}\n| ''Edwin's Lucky Thirteen''\n| Honor\n|\n|- style=\"background:LemonChiffon; color:black\"\n| 2006\n| {{sort|Sheppard,Gloria Armand|Gloria Armand Sheppard}}\n| ''Love Twelve Miles Long''\n| Winner\n| ''2011''\n|- \n| 2006\n| {{sort|Bates,Janet Costa|Janet Costa Bates}}\n| ''Seaside Dream''\n| Honor\n| 2010\n|- \n|